< text>
Again I would be giving this particular starbucks 3 1/3* but there are no halves.
So here goes, starbucks is not my first choice for coffee.   I have found a coffee from starbucks that I absolutely have to have.  However they are by far the most convenient and I'm usually picking coffee for someone else so it just easier.   It's unfortunate that starbucks stop brewing their dark roast or French roast after a certain time as that pretty much all I drink but if I wait they will happily make it for me which I appreciate.  Aside from being convenient they are also consistent.  But what stands out at this location are the baristas that work there.  To say ppl friendly would be an understatement. And that is why I always choose to pick up coffee from this location. And unless the CS falls off a cliff(and it have to be a pretty long cliff) I will be returning.  Oh btw I have had ppl comment on how I sleep drinking such strong coffee so late in the a.m. or even afternoon.  Well my kids jokes that if I ever have a problem falling asleep, all i have to do is drink so coffee....<//text>

<username>awnesha monrreal<//username></record>
</dataset><record>
<response>None</response><Date>1570723128865</Date><rating>5< /rating>< text>
Food halls are a great invention. We love finding them when we travel. This one was great as usual.

We ate at Pizza Bocca Lupo, Konjoe Burger Bar, and Treatbot. All of it was delicious.

We loved being able to try a little bit of food from several places.

This hall was interesting because there were two different buildings separated by an outdoor patio. We loved the outdoor patio. It was the perfect place to enjoy our meal on a nice day.

We got there at 4 and not all of the vendors were open. The vendor list on the map was also out of date.

We were easily able to get parking right outside on the street. It's free on the street after 6 and $2/hr before that.

I'd highly recommend coming here for a meal while in San Jose!</text>

This is such an iconic and historical place that comes highly recommended to anyone who's in San Jose either for the very first time or revisiting after a very long time.

<user_id>107289118146606268960< /user_id>< Text>
Visiting San Jose Downtown? Great. Coming to San Pedro Square? Even better.

With so many flavors to offer, San Pedro Square is just what you might need, once you're in SJ.

I got a chance to visit San Pedro Square last week with a group of friends. The best part is you get to choose out of many food options like Italian, Vietnamese, Japanese & Irish food joints and everything is just a walk away.

Use public transport or private vehicle without having to worry about parking. Multiple garages based at nearby locations.

PS- Downtown Farmer's Market every Friday (May-Nov) from 10-2.

#Day4</Text>

<Rate>4</Rate>< text>
San Pedro Square has something for everyone and for every budget.  It has dining, arts, entertainment, health and beauty salons, pubs and more. San Pedro Square hosts the San Jose Jazz Festival, Cinequest Film Festival, live music events, arts and music festival, and Tour of California cycling race.  There are nearly 1400 parking spaces at the Market-San Pedro Garage or parking along the streets.  There is so much to do and see here and worth a visit.</text>

After over a week of email correspondence to try and find myself a car, I finally scheduled a meeting with the lady I had been emailing to test drive and crunch the numbers for my options. <rating>5< /rating>< review>
Very fun place to climb. Little children to seniors, beginners to experts, all are made to feel welcome. Friendly attentive staff are serious about safety. I look forward to my weekly visits there with my teenage and adult children. This is a fun place to take visitors from out of town with plenty of close by restaurants and shops.<//review>

<Review>"You wear the hat, the hat doesn't wear you!" Tall Tara replied to my "I don't look good in hats, I just love the style." I go into almost every hat shop I come across but this day was different. That statement stuck with me as Tall Tara passed me hat after hat telling me to keep trying them on and see which one didn't look as bad as others and soon I started to see things different. This one didn't look as funny as that one and before long I was holding on to one or two that looked OK on me and then I found THE ONE. I don't buy junk so I was in the right place. You can tell this is a quality work of art. I was ready but one problem, I wanted black. Tall Tara checked and checked but couldn't find one around any of the near by shops. "Wait... you said you are from Seattle?" One last call to their store in Seattle and my new hat was on it's way to my house to meet me when I returned. A quick care and tips session from Tall Tara and I was out the door with a smile on my face and a strong desire to get home to my new hat. < Review>
90% of these hats are not made in the US and come from overseas. $45 for a hat that cost someone $4 to make, if that. If you do find a good hat, it's too expensive. Do yourself a favor and go to Berkeley Hat Company on Telegraph Ave. Killer hats of all makes Stetson, Mayser, Dobbs, etc., and, cheaper than anyone else. Staff is a little eccentric, but hey, it's Berkeley. Carry lots of classics, not passing fads that try and pass for a brim worn by most 16 year olds or community college wannabes wearing skinny jeans walking down the street and smoking cloves. Scope it out!</Review>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<UserId.>104841941530211795257< /UserId.><Name>Zion Strack</Name><Time>1539621296089</Time><rate>5</rate>< Text>
Great service and great selection.</Text>
<pics>None<//pics><Resp>None< /Resp><gmapID>0x808580f10fd5399d:0x92004adb1356fd27< /gmapID></record>
</dataset><record>
< response>
None< /response>
<text>Goorin Brothers Hat Shop keeps with the traditional craftsmanship and details of the old world hat shops for generations, but uses modern sizing, a variety of fabrics and styles to really keep things both where they should be and point to where we're going.

Maybe it's because I own a slew of Pendletons, but somehow I purchased a Tribly that perfectly matches a Vintage Pendleton I own. Not only the material, but the accenting piece. It wasn't your traditional wool which almost every traditional hat was made from, but the seams and sewing really helped the hat keep shape. Some friends I went here with also bought a straw Tribly and a few other styles. Granted I haven't been to the other Goorin Brothers shops, the design of the shop reminded me of 5 & a Dime in SD, ironically near where they are opening a new shop in San Diego. More of a library style shelving with intricate dark stained wood and mirrors with hardwood floors and a loft above the front register. Tall ceilings and since I went in the first month or so they were really trying to move inventory to make room for new models.

I bought a can of the Raindri which is manufactured specifically for Goorin Brothers shops is similar to scotch guard, but designed specifically for fabrics and items designed to be dry clean only. Unlike many other weather guards this does not stain, so there is no need for color safing. Unlike many other's this is aerosol and mists the best because it's often designed to cling to all the many fibers of wool.

The staff is great, not pushy at all. I knew I wanted to buy, but I felt them out and realized they suggested based on me not being a Joe Schmo off the street wanting a Fedora, yet knowing the difference between that and a Trilby.

If I didn't use so much Suavecito Pomade product in my hair and spend so much time looking clean I'd wear more hats and I'd buy them from Goorin Brothers. Can't wait for the SD shop to open at the old Vans location. It could be the trifecta of getting a traditional haircut and straight razor shave at Lefty's, walking to 5 & A Dime and getting crisp clothing and then walking to Goorin to finish the look and your ready for anything.<//text>< user_id>

< Review>
Thank you Alex!  I truly appreciate you help with the car today.

10/8/19 - I had to edit my review.  While the salesman was quite helpful, I had to downgrade my review because of the car itself.

Got a 2009 Chevy Equinox  and trust me, I understand a used car is gonna have issue but I didn't think that it would be 30 days after I got it.

There was a few issues with the car - cylinder misfire prompted me to take the car in and the diagnostic found that it needed a new engine (which they paid for)  but I also need a new catalytic converter (they don't pay for and will cost me around $800), a new thermostat,  and something else that was on the estimate.

Oh so when I called to see if I could make a payment arrangement to get the converter fixed, I was told that I CANT pay later cause you have to make on time payments for the first 6 months (don't remember seeing that anywhere in the paperwork).  So since I know that they will just cut the car off for non payment, I made the payment and have to wait on the repairs.

Its also too late to return the car since it was past the 7 day return policy.

Also they tell you that you have to do autopay.  DONT DO IT!

I had it.  Was told that my payment would come out every other Friday (which is fine since I get paid on that day).  The first payment was due on the 30 via autopay.  When it didnt come out that day, the next morning I paid it.

The following weekday, the autopay kicked in and overdrew my account.  I wrote my account manager and to this day, I still haven't heard back from him.

Unfortunately, I will have to tell people to really consider their options when coming here.  And if possible, go somewhere else.< /Review>

< text>
There is good stuff and bad stuff about this dealership... First off I did refrain from reviewing this place while I was there and had just been approved for a car. It was asked of me to do so and I almost did it just because I was so relieved and happy to be getting a car but I stopped myself because I wanted to make sure that I put my entire experience in this review. So yes we did get a car. We were their 4 1/2 hours. Yup it took that long. My situation is no credit but I own my own business and make good money. So I brought in all the  necessary paperwork, proof of income etc. After a couple of hours our information was ‚Äúsent up‚Äù to whoever they send it to to get approved ... There was some back and forth , then our car salesmen says he is going to let us test drive a vehicle. We thought hey we are finally getting somewhere. So he went off to get keys and my husband and I are wondering why he didn‚Äôt ask us which car we wanted  to test drive...We follow him outside and we walk towards the car we want to test drive but he quickly tells us that we are to test drive another vehicle that we don‚Äôt even want. We told him no thank you ,we would like to test drive this other car... my husband at this point is just fed up at the whole thing and wanted to leave. I told him no let‚Äôs stand our ground and see if we can get something we actually want. I get the feeling that this place takes advantage of ppl in desperate situations and excepts them to accept whatever car they put them in. The car he wanted us to test drive had a broken handle on the passenger side door so you couldn‚Äôt open it from the inside, yes it‚Äôs not a big fix but it‚Äôs definitely not something you want to see in a car you are buying.. So once again more information was collected from us and ‚Äúsent up‚Äù to the approval gods because I guess now we need special consideration to be able to buy a car that we want. And the thing that we didn‚Äôt understand is that we have brought in about $8000 twice a month for several years. Didn‚Äôt have any outstanding bills didn‚Äôt have any creditors after us we just didn‚Äôt have any credit. But very employed and making more then enough money to make a decent size car payment, easily. So at about the 4th hour in we are finally okayed to look at some more options. The one that we wanted we still weren‚Äôt allowed to look at because of ‚Äútitle issues.‚Äù Okay whatever...Instead of having a price tag on it maybe put a sign in the window that says ‚Äúnot for sale‚Äù like the other vehicles that weren‚Äôt for sale had in their windows..Anyways we test drove another SUV and I fell in love with it so we bought it. Okay other tidbits...they make you sit through and watch the silliest ‚Äúpresentations.‚Äù  It frustrating and time consuming..The car selection sucks, we found nails in tires, broken door handles and locks...it‚Äôs just a messy place. The hours we spent there we saw a lot of ppl come in but didn‚Äôt see anyone leave with a car. I over heard one guy being told that he needed a co-signer..With all this being said, I think this type of place can be a great stepping stone for ppl like us to finally build credit. I also think that they have a great warranty program..It doesn‚Äôt cover door handles and nails in tires though...lol Would I buy a car from carhop again,,,yes! Would I go to this location again ? I‚Äôd have to say no. Advice is,,try and not to be desperate stand ur ground a bit and hopefully you can get what you want. Good luck!!!</text>

There is good stuff and bad stuff about this dealership... First off I did refrain from reviewing this place while I was there and had just been approved for a car. It was asked of me to do so and I almost did it just because I was so relieved and happy to be getting a car but I stopped myself because I wanted to make sure that I put my entire experience in this review. So yes we did get a car. We were their 4 1/2 hours. Yup it took that long. My situation is no credit but I own my own business and make good money. So I brought in all the  necessary paperwork, proof of income etc. After a couple of hours our information was ‚Äúsent up‚Äù to whoever they send it to to get approved ... There was some back and forth , then our car salesmen says he is going to let us test drive a vehicle. We thought hey we are finally getting somewhere. So he went off to get keys and my husband and I are wondering why he didn‚Äôt ask us which car we wanted  to test drive...We follow him outside and we walk towards the car we want to test drive but he quickly tells us that we are to test drive another vehicle that we don‚Äôt even want. We told him no thank you ,we would like to test drive this other car... my husband at this point is just fed up at the whole thing and wanted to leave. I told him no let‚Äôs stand our ground and see if we can get something we actually want. I get the feeling that this place takes advantage of ppl in desperate situations and excepts them to accept whatever car they put them in. The car he wanted us to test drive had a broken handle on the passenger side door so you couldn‚Äôt open it from the inside, yes it‚Äôs not a big fix but it‚Äôs definitely not something you want to see in a car you are buying.. So once again more information was collected from us and ‚Äúsent up‚Äù to the approval gods because I guess now we need special consideration to be able to buy a car that we want. And the thing that we didn‚Äôt understand is that we have brought in about $8000 twice a month for several years. Didn‚Äôt have any outstanding bills didn‚Äôt have any creditors after us we just didn‚Äôt have any credit. But very employed and making more then enough money to make a decent size car payment, easily. So at about the 4th hour in we are finally okayed to look at some more options. The one that we wanted we still weren‚Äôt allowed to look at because of ‚Äútitle issues.‚Äù Okay whatever...Instead of having a price tag on it maybe put a sign in the window that says ‚Äúnot for sale‚Äù like the other vehicles that weren‚Äôt for sale had in their windows..Anyways we test drove another SUV and I fell in love with it so we bought it. Okay other tidbits...they make you sit through and watch the silliest ‚Äúpresentations.‚Äù  It frustrating and time consuming..The car selection sucks, we found nails in tires, broken door handles and locks...it‚Äôs just a messy place. The hours we spent there we saw a lot of ppl come in but didn‚Äôt see anyone leave with a car. I over heard one guy being told that he needed a co-signer..With all this being said, I think this type of place can be a great stepping stone for ppl like us to finally build credit. I also think that they have a great warranty program..It doesn‚Äôt cover door handles and nails in tires though...lol Would I buy a car from carhop again,,,yes! Would I go to this location again ? I‚Äôd have to say no. Advice is,,try and not to be desperate stand ur ground a bit and hopefully you can get what you want. Good luck!!!<//review>
